xvfb-static: load a compiled-in keymap (no rules file, no xkbcomp)

What: patches xkb/ddxLoad.c (the same single file xserver-0001 already
patches) so XkbCompileKeymapForDevice() returns a keymap read straight out
of a `static const unsigned char xvfb_static_keymap_xkm[]` array compiled into the
binary, instead of building one from the filesystem.

Upstream's path was two filesystem-bound steps:

  XkbCompileKeymapForDevice
    -> XkbRMLVOtoKcCGST -> XkbDDXNamesFromRules   opens <xkbdir>/rules/evdev
    -> XkbDDXLoadKeymapByNames
         -> XkbDDXCompileKeymapByNames -> RunXkbComp   fork+execv xkbcomp
         -> LoadXKM -> XkmReadFile(FILE *)             reads, then unlinks

Note the FIRST step: the rules lookup happens BEFORE anything is compiled, so
a prebuilt .xkm alone does NOT free the pack from the data tree -- pointing
-xkbdir at an empty directory dies in XkbDDXNamesFromRules with a message
("XKB: Failed to compile keymap") that misleadingly blames the compile step.
Hooking at XkbCompileKeymapForDevice bypasses BOTH steps in one move; that is
why the hook is here and not further down. Verified empirically before this
patch was written -- see docs/superpowers/specs/2026-07-20-precompiled-keymap-findings.md.

Why this is tractable at all: LoadXKM reads the keymap through
XkmReadFile(FILE *file, ...). Because the reader takes a FILE *, fmemopen()
feeds it the embedded bytes directly -- no output directory, no temp file, no
unlink, no process spawn, no filesystem access of any kind. fmemopen() is
POSIX.1-2008 and present in musl, this pack's only libc (pkgsStatic).

What this buys the pack: bin/xkbcomp (1.5 MB) and share/xkb/ (580 KB, 54
files) both become unreachable and ARE now deleted from the pack, along with a
fork+execv from every single display start. The 28 blobs total 375,096 bytes.

Scope of the behavior change: the Xvfb binary serves only the curated embedded
catalog selected by the VFB parser. That is a real capability reduction and a
STATED decision, not a side effect of a size optimization. RMLVO arguments are
ignored; the parameters remain because the signature is fixed by both call
sites in this file.

Fail-loud (tenet 5), and why it needed care: upstream's KeymapOrDefaults()
answers a NULL from this function by logging "Failed to load keymap. Loading
default keymap instead." and re-entering it with need == 0. That is exactly
the silent degradation tenet 5 forbids, and it is invisible in ordinary
testing because a default keymap still yields a working-looking server. It is
defused structurally rather than by deleting upstream code: the retry reads
the SAME embedded blob, so a rejected blob fails the retry too,
XkbCompileKeymap() returns NULL, and the server dies in InitCoreDevices()
with FatalError("Failed to activate virtual core keyboard") (dix/devices.c).
Confirmed by corrupting a byte of the blob, rebuilding, and watching the
server abort -- not by reading the code.

...but "the retry reads the same blob" is only half the story, and the first
cut of this patch got the other half wrong (caught in code review, 2026-07-20).
Re-reading the same bad blob only guarantees the same OUTCOME if the accept/
reject test is the same on both calls -- and it was not. Upstream's retained
(need & provided) != need test evaluates to (0 & provided) != 0 on the retry,
which is ALWAYS false, leaving only the `xkb == NULL` guard. XkmReadFile() has
two rejection shapes and that guard covers just one of them: a bad TOC returns
before XkbAllocKeyboard(), but a bad SECTION past a valid TOC ALLOCATES *xkb
and returns it partially populated (xkmread.c:1242). So on the retry the
second shape produced a non-NULL, half-loaded XkbDescPtr and the server booted
on it. That shape is newly reachable precisely because of this patch: upstream's
retry recompiled the default RMLVO from the data tree and normally succeeded,
whereas ours re-reads the same bad blob. The fix is to test against a FIXED
local requirement (`xvfb_static_need`) rather than the caller's `need`, and to pass
that same fixed mask to XkmReadFile() -- making this function's verdict wholly
independent of what the caller asked for, which is the honest description of a
server that ships only precompiled keymaps. See the function comment for the mask set
and why it is the right requirement.

Removed with it: the static XkbRMLVOtoKcCGST(), whose only caller was the
body replaced here. Left in place it would be an unreferenced static
(-Wunused-function). Its callee XkbDDXNamesFromRules() is an exported entry
point (include/xkbsrv.h) and stays.

Second hook, added when bin/xkbcomp was deleted from the pack: reject the
string-keymap entry point, XkbCompileKeymapFromString().

The first cut of this patch left that path alone and flagged it: RunXkbComp()
was still reachable from XkbDDXLoadKeymapFromString(), i.e. from
XkbCompileKeymapFromString(). That was defensible while bin/xkbcomp still
shipped; with the binary gone, anything reaching it would fork+execv a path
that does not exist and surface as a confusing exec failure naming a missing
tool, rather than as the true answer -- this pack ships only embedded keymaps and
cannot compile another. So the function now returns NULL after saying so.

Precision about HOW reachable it is, since the code-review note that prompted
this called it "the server's -keymap command-line option" and that turns out
to be wrong FOR THIS BINARY (found by running, not reading):

  Xvfb :95 -screen 0 1280x1024x24 -keymap something
  -> (EE) Unrecognized option: -keymap
     Fatal server error / (EE) Unrecognized option: -keymap

Xvfb's argument parser does not accept -keymap at all; nothing in this tree
does. XkbCompileKeymapFromString()'s only caller is
InitKeyboardDeviceStructFromString() (xkb/xkbInit.c), which is an _X_EXPORT
API (include/input.h) with NO in-tree caller in an Xvfb-only build -- upstream
it is Xwayland's path, and this pack configures --disable-xwayland. So the
path was ALREADY unreachable before bin/xkbcomp was deleted, and the deletion
did not create a live failure mode; it created a latent one, contingent on
some future ddx or build variant calling that exported entry point.

Kept anyway, for two reasons that stand on their own: the diagnostic is
correct and free in the unreachable case, and closing the function is what
lets the two now-unreferenced statics below be deleted with it. Verified by
running that the message is compiled into the shipped binary (grep -a on
bin/Xvfb finds both lines); it is not currently printable from any CLI
invocation, and that is stated here rather than left for the next reader to
discover.

It returns NULL rather than delegating to KeymapOrDefaults() (which is what
upstream's version does with a failed compile). KeymapOrDefaults() would fall
through to XkbCompileKeymapForDevice(), succeed on the embedded keymap, and
boot as though -keymap had been honoured -- a silent substitution of a
DIFFERENT layout than the one explicitly requested, which is precisely what
tenet 5 forbids and what the rest of this patch works to prevent. NULL instead
routes into the caller's existing failure handling (xkbInit.c logs "XKB: Failed
to compile keymap" and unwinds, ending in FatalError("Failed to activate
virtual core keyboard")), so the server refuses to start -- rather than booting
on a keymap other than the one that was explicitly requested.

Removed with it: the statics xkb_write_keymap_string_cb() and
XkbDDXLoadKeymapFromString() (plus the XkbKeymapString struct they shared),
whose only caller was the body replaced here -- same -Wunused-function
reasoning as XkbRMLVOtoKcCGST() above. RunXkbComp() itself survives and still
compiles: XkbDDXLoadKeymapByNames() calls it and is an exported entry point
(include/xkbsrv.h). But it now has no in-tree caller on any reachable path,
which makes xserver-0001's XVFB_STATIC_XKB_BINDIR / XVFB_STATIC_XKM_OUTPUT_DIR overrides and
its shell-less direct-exec machinery effectively dead weight for this pack.
0001 is deliberately left in place regardless -- whether to retire it is a
separate call, not a side effect of this one.

Diagnostics use ErrorF(), not LogMessage() -- found by running, not reading.
The first cut of this patch used LogMessage(X_ERROR, ...) as the task brief
sketched. Corrupting the blob then produced a correctly FATAL server, but the
"xvfb-static: embedded keymap failed to load" line never appeared: LogMessage() logs
at verbosity 1, while logVerbosity defaults to 0 (os/log.c) and Xvfb has no
log file, so the message was silently dropped. A fail-loud diagnostic nobody
can see is not fail-loud. ErrorF() routes to LogVWrite(-1, ...) and always
reaches stderr -- which is what xkbInit.c already does for this very failure.
The same gap is why upstream's KeymapOrDefaults() "Loading default keymap
instead." warning is invisible here too, and it is part of why that silent
substitution is so easy to miss.

The growth is predominantly rationale and deletion of upstream code that became
unreferenced. The runtime addition is the catalog selector and embedded loader;
the VFB argument parser remains isolated in patch 0003.

Generated against the tree with xserver-0001 already applied, which is the
order pack.nix lists them in; both apply cleanly in sequence (verified with
patch --dry-run against a pristine extract of the pinned tarball).

